## MixinExtras Best Practices

When writing Sponge Mixins, **always prefer MixinExtras injectors** over vanilla mixin
patterns. MixinExtras injectors chain when multiple mods target the same code; vanilla
`@Overwrite`, `@Inject` at HEAD with cancel/return, `@Redirect`, and `@ModifyConstant`
do not chain and will silently conflict with other mods.

### Injector Selection Guide

Pick the **most specific** injector that fits the task:

| Goal | Use | Avoid |
|---|---|---|
| Tweak a method's return value | `@ModifyReturnValue` | `@Inject(at = RETURN)` + `cir.setReturnValue(modify(cir.getReturnValue()))` |
| Add/change a condition around an expression | `@ModifyExpressionValue` | `@Redirect` on the boolean call |
| Conditionally skip a void call or field write | `@WrapWithCondition` | `@Redirect` returning default/void |
| Wrap a call/field/instanceof in custom logic | `@WrapOperation` | `@Redirect` |
| Wrap an entire method (try/catch, sync, etc.) | `@WrapMethod` | `@Overwrite` or `@Inject` at HEAD + RETURN |
| Change receiver of a call/field access | `@ModifyReceiver` | `@Redirect` |
| Replace a method wholesale (last resort) | `@Overwrite` only if no other option | — |

### Local Variable Capture

Use MixinExtras `@Local` sugar instead of traditional mixin local capture:

```java
// GOOD — annotation-based, concise, works with any injector
@Inject(method = "use", at = @At(value = "INVOKE", target = "..."))
private void onUse(CallbackInfoReturnable<?> cir, @Local ItemStack stack) {
    stack.shrink(1);
}

// BAD — fragile ordinal-based LocalCapture
@Inject(method = "use", at = @At(value = "INVOKE", target = "..."),
        locals = LocalCapture.CAPTURE_FAILHARD)
private void onUse(Level level, Player player, InteractionHand hand,
                   CallbackInfoReturnable<?> cir,
                   /* every preceding local in order */ ItemStack stack) {
    stack.shrink(1);
}
```

For mutable capture use `LocalRef<T>` / `LocalIntRef` / `LocalDoubleRef` etc.
with `@Local`:
```java
@Inject(method = "target", at = @At(...))
private void mutateLocals(CallbackInfo ci,
                          @Local LocalRef<String> name,
                          @Local LocalIntRef color) {
    name.set("modified");
    color.set(0xFF0000);
}
```

### Sharing Values Between Handlers

Use `@Share` instead of storing values in mixin fields (thread-safe, no long-term
memory):
```java
@ModifyArg(method = "target", at = @At(value = "INVOKE", target = "..."))
private int captureArg(int arg, @Share("myArg") LocalIntRef ref) {
    ref.set(arg);
    return arg;
}

@Inject(method = "target", at = @At("TAIL"))
private void useArg(CallbackInfo ci, @Share("myArg") LocalIntRef ref) {
    doSomething(ref.get());
}
```

### @Cancellable Sugar

Any MixinExtras injector can receive a `@Cancellable CallbackInfo(Returnable)` to
optionally cancel the enclosing method without needing a separate `@Inject`:
```java
@ModifyExpressionValue(method = "render", at = @At(value = "INVOKE", target = "..."))
private Identifier skipPoison(Identifier texture, @Cancellable CallbackInfo ci) {
    if (texture.equals(Textures.POISON_HEART)) ci.cancel();
    return texture;
}
```

### MixinExtras Expressions

For targeting complex bytecode patterns (comparisons, instanceof, compound
expressions) that are hard or impossible to reach with standard `@At`, use
`@Expression` with `@Definition`:

```java
// Target `? instanceof AbstractArrow` in the hurt method
@Definition(id = "AbstractArrow", type = AbstractArrow.class)
@Expression("? instanceof AbstractArrow")
@WrapOperation(method = "hurt", at = @At("MIXINEXTRAS:EXPRESSION"))
private boolean modifyArrowCheck(Object entity, Operation<Boolean> original) {
    return original.call(entity) && someCondition();
}
```

Key rules for Expressions:
- `@At` value must be `"MIXINEXTRAS:EXPRESSION"` — the actual target comes from
  `@Expression`
- `@Definition` annotations bind identifiers to fields, methods, types, or locals
- Use `?` wildcards for parts you don't care about matching
- Strings use single quotes inside `@Expression` (it's already in a Java string)
- Built-in identifiers like `this` don't need a `@Definition`
- Expressions target the "last" instruction unless you explicitly mark a target with
  `@(...)` syntax

### Quick Reference: When NOT to Use Vanilla Patterns

- **`@Overwrite`**: Almost never needed. Use `@WrapMethod` to wrap, or a combination
  of injectors. Overwrites break ALL other mods targeting the same method.
- **`@Inject` at HEAD + `ci.cancel()`/`cir.setReturnValue()`**: Prevents other mods'
  injections from running. Use `@WrapMethod` or `@ModifyReturnValue` instead.
- **`@Redirect`**: Does not chain. Use `@WrapOperation` (wraps + chains),
  `@ModifyExpressionValue` (tweak result + chains), `@WrapWithCondition` (conditional
  skip + chains), or `@ModifyReceiver` (swap receiver + chains).
- **`@ModifyConstant`**: Does not chain. Use `@ModifyExpressionValue` on the constant
  expression instead.
- **`locals = LocalCapture.CAPTURE_FAILHARD`**: Fragile and verbose. Use `@Local` sugar.

There are exceptions — sometimes `@Inject` at HEAD with cancel is the only practical
option (e.g., returning early on the client side before any logic runs, as in
`AquaGrandmasterEntityMixin`). Use your judgment, but default to MixinExtras.
